        <p class="intro">
         Four days wildlife watching in the Pantanal ending with a face-to-face meeting with the animal at the top of my wanted list.
        </p>
        If this was the icing on the cake, it was pretty special icing on a pretty special cake.
        <br/>
        <br/>
        My wife and I were in Brazil,on the first leg of a 4-week adventure through southern South America. Since we both retired in early 2011, weve taken to
        <br/>
        having two or three longish trips each year, visiting different parts of the
        <br/>
        world and having a variety of experiences when were there. Last autumn we put together a trip to include some bits of Brazil, a few days dancing Tango in Buenos Aires and a fortnight in Patagonia. At this point we had come to the end of a few days enjoying the wildlife in the Pantanal, and were on the road back to Cuiaba to catch our plane on to Iguassu falls.
        <br/>
        <br/>
        The Pantanal is a very special place. A true wetland, vast areas are flooded by the end of the rainy season. Even now, at the end of the dry season, the
        <br/>
        lake near our Pousada was over 10 kilometres across (with an average depth of less than a meter, we were told). We were assigned a very entertaining and very knowledgeable guide to help us make the most of the abundant wildlife. Italian by birth, Carlo had trained as a research chemist before a varied career took him to Brazil via Stevenage and the US. Exactly how he ended up as a wildlife guide we never managed to work out, but he did it very well. For four days he took us round the area, on foot, in boats (motorised or paddled) and by jeep, and he knew the names of practically every one of the 100-plus bird species he pointed out to us. His explanations were always amusing, not least because every other sentence was enlivened by the phrase Mamma mia!, said with true Italian feeling.
        <br/>
        <br/>
        One morning Carlo and our boat captain arranged a spectacular demonstration for us. One of the most impressive bird species thriving on the abundant fish in the shallow waters is the black-collared hawk. Like
        <br/>
        other fish-eating raptors, they swoop to take fish from the water with their
        <img alt="exp-add-the-title-of-your-article-here-eg-gorilla-trekking-in-rwanda1.jpg" class="pad" src="http://cdn.wanderlust.co.uk/contentimages/userimages/Mike%20Segal/exp-add-the-title-of-your-article-here-eg-gorilla-trekking-in-rwanda1.jpg?maxwidth=250" style="float: right;" title="exp-add-the-title-of-your-article-here-eg-gorilla-trekking-in-rwanda1.jpg"/>
        magnificent talons. What is astonishing is the speed with which they take their
        <br/>
        prey. Three times our captain threw a dead piranha into the water, and each time a hawk appeared in a flash. We managed to get a few photographs and a short video of this performance, and I mean short. The whole video is 3 seconds long, and the
        <br/>
        bird appears, snatches the fish in its claws and flies off in literally a
        <br/>
        fraction of a second.
        <br/>
        <br/>
        <br/>
        <br/>
        As well as the birds, the water and its margins are home to a range of fascinating creatures. Caiman in astonishing numbers basked on the
        <br/>
        riverbanks or floated motionless in the water, now and then striking suddenly
        <br/>
        with a loud splash as a fish came within reach. Capybara, looking fat and
        <br/>
        comfortable, wandered slowly among the bushes or sat impassively by the waters edge. We spotted a couple of iguanas, including one bright green juvenile. Other interesting sightings included howler and capuchin monkeys, wild guinea-pigs, a vinegar scorpion (looking exactly like a large scorpion, but in fact an insect) and a very hairy tarantula.
        <br/>
        <br/>
        There were two animals I particularly wanted to see on this trip, the giant river otter and the giant anteater. Our previous attempt to see giant otters in South America had been rather unsuccessful, as we had seen them only at a distance, and for a few moments. This time we were luckier. On our last full day in the Pantanal, as we drifted slowly along the Rio Mutum in the early morning, we became aware of a small furry head moving through the water towards us. The otter lifted his head up and took a good look, before diving out of sight. A few minutes later I was watching
        <img alt="exp-add-the-title-of-your-article-here-eg-gorilla-trekking-in-rwanda2.jpg" class="pad" src="http://cdn.wanderlust.co.uk/contentimages/userimages/Mike%20Segal/exp-add-the-title-of-your-article-here-eg-gorilla-trekking-in-rwanda2.jpg?maxwidth=250" style="float: right;" title="exp-add-the-title-of-your-article-here-eg-gorilla-trekking-in-rwanda2.jpg"/>
        a family of capybara on the bank when the boatman tapped me on the shoulder
        <br/>
        with his paddle and pointed to an otter on the bank, only a few meters away. I
        <br/>
        had just a momentary sight of its sleek body and long, flat tail as it waddled
        <br/>
        into the water and disappeared.
        <br/>
        <br/>
        <br/>
        <br/>
        Top of my list, though, was the giant anteater. They are
        <br/>
        magnificent creatures, amongst the most handsome of all mammals in my opinion, and we might never get another chance to see them in the wild. They live only in central and South America and they are not exactly abundant
        <br/>
        (technically classified as threatened by the IUCN). In our four days at the
        <br/>
        Pousada we saw no sign of them.
        <br/>
        <br/>
        At the end of our stay, Carlo accompanied us on the drive along the narrow country roads back to Cuiaba, where his wife and our plane awaited. Suddenly, for no apparent reason, Claudio the driver pulled up by the side of the road. After a minute of conversation in Portuguese, Carlo turned to us and said this was the field where anteaters were sometimes found and Claudio reckoned he could see a couple in the distance. We leapt out of the car and rushed to the fence to see. Far in the distance, a couple of animals were moving slowly through the long grass. We could barely make them out  how Claudio had spotted them while driving was a mystery. I rushed back to the car to get my long telephoto lens Would we like to go closer? You bet we would. So they helped us through the fence and we walked slowly and quietly towards the anteaters, stopping regularly to take photographs as they gradually stood out more clearly. They werent the slightest bit bothered as we approached. After a few minutes I was standing no more than a few meters from the animal I most wanted to see, virtually face to face. He looked calmly at me and I did my best to remain equally calm. We stood there,
        <img alt="exp-add-the-title-of-your-article-here-eg-gorilla-trekking-in-rwanda.JPG" class="pad" src="http://cdn.wanderlust.co.uk/contentimages/userimages/Mike%20Segal/exp-add-the-title-of-your-article-here-eg-gorilla-trekking-in-rwanda.JPG?maxwidth=250" style="float: right;" title="exp-add-the-title-of-your-article-here-eg-gorilla-trekking-in-rwanda.JPG"/>
        peacefully looking at each other, until Claudio indicated it was time to leave.
        <br/>
        <br/>
        <br/>
        As I walked happily back to the car I thought to myself this truly was the icing on the cake.
        <br/>
        <br/>

  <script type="text/javascript">
   var g_ext = null;
        window.onload = function () {
            try {
                if (window.external.msIsSiteMode()) {
                    g_ext = window.external;
                    g_ext.msSiteModeCreateJumpList("Wanderlust Hubs");
                    g_ext.msSiteModeAddJumpListItem('Plan A Trip', 'http://www.wanderlust.co.uk/planatrip/', 'http://www.wanderlust.co.uk/favicon.ico');
                    g_ext.msSiteModeAddJumpListItem('MyWanderlust', 'http://www.wanderlust.co.uk/mywanderlust/', 'http://www.wanderlust.co.uk/favicon.ico');
                    g_ext.msSiteModeAddJumpListItem('Magazine', 'http://www.wanderlust.co.uk/magazine/', 'http://www.wanderlust.co.uk/favicon.ico');
                    g_ext.msSiteModeShowJumplist();
                    g_ext.msSiteModeCreateJumpList("Wanderlust Today");
                    $.ajax({
                        type: "POST",
                        url: "/Services/sitecontent.asmx/GetSiteLatest",
                        data: "{}",
                        contentType: "application/json; charset=utf-8",
                        dataType: "json",
                        success: function (response) {
                            var list = response.d;
                            $('#output').empty();
                            $.each(list, function (index, list) {
                                g_ext.msSiteModeAddJumpListItem(list.Name, list.Url, "http://www.wanderlust.co.uk/favicon.ico");  
                            });
                        },
                        failure: function (msg) {                            
                        }
                    });                   
                    g_ext.msSiteModeShowJumplist();
                }
            }
            catch (ex) {
                // Fail silently.
            }
        }
  </script>
  <script type="text/javascript">
   $(document).ready(function () {

            $(".topMenuAction").click(function () {

                if ($("#openCloseIdentifier").hasClass("close")) {

                    $("#sliderPanel").animate({
                        marginLeft: "0px"
                    }, 500);
                    $("#topMenuImage").html('&lt;img src="http://cdn.wanderlust.co.uk/img/ui/subscribe_close.png" alt="close" title="Subscribe to Wanderlust Travel Magazine" /&gt;');

                    $("#openCloseIdentifier").removeClass("close");

                } else {
                    $("#sliderPanel").animate({
                        marginLeft: "-300px"
                    }, 500);

                    $("#topMenuImage").html('&lt;img src="http://cdn.wanderlust.co.uk/img/ui/subscribe_open.png" alt="open" title="Subscribe to Wanderlust Travel Magazine" /&gt;');
                    $("#openCloseIdentifier").addClass("close");
                }
            });
        });
  </script>
  <script type="text/javascript">
   $(document).ready(function () {
            try {
                $("#flowpanes").scrollable().autoscroll({ interval: 3000 }).circular();
            } catch (e) { }

            try {
                $('#divMostRead').hide();
                $('a#tabLatest').addClass('active');
                $('a#tabMostRead');

                $('a#tabLatest').click(function () {
                    $('#divLatest').show('slow');
                    $('#divMostRead').hide('fast');
                    $(this).addClass('active');
                    $('a#tabMostRead').removeClass('active');
                    return false;
                });

                $('a#tabMostRead').click(function () {
                    $('#divMostRead').show('slow');
                    $('#divLatest').hide('fast');
                    $(this).addClass('active');
                    $('a#tabLatest').removeClass('active');
                    return false;
                });

                $("#myScroll").scrollable().circular();
            } catch (e) { }
        });
  </script>
